node.text:
#ReginaHall is our September cover star—and wellness is top of mind for her after turning 50 during the pandemic: "I think it enforced that you can't take anything for granted," says Hall. "You have to have gratitude for every day that you have."
.
This lesson is reminiscent of one that @morereginahall learned much earlier in her life. Hall was in her early 20s and in grad school to be a journalist when her father unexpectedly passed away. "It was his passing that really shifted how I looked at life—I realized how brief it can be and how suddenly it can change.” 
.
To feel her best, Hall says, “I love when I eat right and when I feel spiritually centered and connected. I love when I'm meditating—that ebbs and flows.” She also prioritizes taking care of her skin. “I always wash my face before bed. I've always moisturized, too. Now I use argan oil on my face. Your skin changes—it's different in your 20s than it is in your 30s than it is in your 40s and so on. So you have to constantly be looking at your complexion and assessing what it needs.“
.

node.text:
"When I became pregnant with my daughter, I was prepared for the numerous changes that pregnancy can have on your body; I'd been thoroughly warned about swollen ankles and an achy back," explains writer Caroline Chirichella. "What I didn't know was that the digestive system issues I experienced in the days after having my baby—constipation, diarrhea, and hemorrhoids—would continue long after I gave birth."
.
Here, we break down what you need to know before giving birth. Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Having a Baby Can Completely Change the Way You Poop Here's What You Should Know Health'.

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What are some digestive system issues you might experience after giving birth? Constipation Diarrhea Hemorrhoids Fecal incontinence (aka, the inability to control your bowels) Health'.

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says '50% of women experience constipation immediately after delivery 24% of oninu women continue to experience constipation at 3 months postpartum Health'.

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Why do these bowel movement changes happen? The soreness and pain after childbirth can limit the ability to bear down and, therefore, the ability to go No. 2. Medication for postpartum pain can make your bowels slower, resulting in constipation. Your bowel movements greatly depend on the integrity of your pelvic floor, which just went through something major and needs time to recover. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Why do these bowel movement changes happen? Pelvic floor changes often result in constipation, which in turn causes hemorrhoids during and after birth. Progesterone levels are higher during pregnancy, which can slow down your entire GI tract. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Here's how doctors recommend treating these postpartum bowel issues: Hemorrhoids Increase dietary fiber and water intake Use stool softeners, hydrocortisone creams and suppositories, and sitz baths Constipation Eat a high-fiber diet and drink plenty of water Take fiber supplements, stool softeners, and/or a laxative Health'.

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Here's how doctors recommend treating these postpartum bowel issues: Fecal incontinence and diarrhea Use fiber supplements/bulking agents and anti-diarrheal agents Start pelvic physical therapy at four to six weeks after delivery (and continue for least five months) Health'.
